But hey!!! It’s ridiculous to take away grades for youbg children!! It’s not like it’s an arbitrary method of evaluating learning that systematically punishes people with learning disabilities.
It’s not like some people are abused at home because of their grades, even as kids.

I was so constantly belittled and humiliated in primary school, that when I got to middle school, the first time a professor told me I had a perfect score, I didn’t believe them and thought they had confused me with someone else.
That was the year I finally got diagnosed and started meds. When I started improving at school she thought it was her severe punishments that made me get better.

Yes, I’m measuring my words when I use the word abuse.

Remind me to tell you the story about how my third grade teacher was diagnosed by a licensed psychologist to have an irrational hate towards me.

I was miserable all throughout 3rd grade because I was punished at every turn.

And to just sit there and listen to dozens of people think that my hardships growing up and the way I was ABUSED at school are just stuff that could never be taken seriously by any rational person is infuriating.
It’s still ableist as shit, but because it’s “just ADHD” it’s “not that serious” and I’m just a fucking “killjoy”.

I was thinking what if this same fucking “comedian” was making a similar sketch about accommodations for autistic kids??

It would be considered unacceptable.

Yet, ADHD and ASD are first cousins. Maybe even siblings.

I will never forgive media for the portrayal it did of ADHD.

No one ever takes us fucking seriously.
No one thinks it’s real or a valid diagnosis as an adult.
Everyone thinks you outgrow it.
People think it was made up by pharmaceuticals (which, lol bc it’s so hard to get meds)

“A kid with ‘a lot of potential’ doesn’t exist. It’s what parents say to not admit their kid is an ass”

NO, ITS WHAT EVERY TEACHER TOLD US ABOUT HOW WE WERE SMART BUT TOO LAZY TO DO ANYTHING ABOUT IT.

Jesus fcking Christ.

“When I was a kid, children who couldn’t sit still for 5 minutes, didn’t do hood in school and wouldn’t listen to instructions were just called stupid”.

We know. We heard that a thousand times growing up.
Yes, ADHD is a neurological disorder and due to our society’s expectation of being productive, it IS a disability.
If I ever have to listen to another “comedian” use disability they don’t even understand for their sketch, I will personally destroy their career.

I’ve chichatted with women on public transportation before and none have ever been as invasive as men. I WONDER WHY.

And yes, I totally understood and felt sympathetic for a lot of the stuff he was saying: Parisians are rude, won’t stop to help anyone, won’t give a smile to no one, etc.

But dude. Even if I’m friendly enough to give directions and chitchat a bit, there are BOUNDARIES.
(Yes, he asked for all of this).
A total stranger doesn’t get to know my origins, my story, my job, my hobbies, my parents’ place of residence, my real name nor my real phone number.

He KNEW I wasn’t French (again, because I spoke English too well) but I just kept saying I was.

He asked if both my parents were French. I said they were and that they lived in the South of France, lmaooo.

I almost always do this when strangers ask me about me in public places. Sometimes friends wonder why, as if I’m ashamed or something.

I’m not, but strangers are not entitled to my life story just cause they asked.

He was telling how people in Paris barely help him (I told him at which station he should get off the train) and started asking questions about my life.

And so, I lied.
Did I just give a quite friendly man a fake number ? Yes, yes I did.

I honestly don’t have to justify why I left my country 6 years to someone I just met at someone else’s party, leave me tf alone.

After many years, I finally figured what bothers me about these question that people ask me all the time. It’s that complete strangers feel entitled to know my life’s story just because they’re curious.

Je ne vais pas faire la liste de toutes choses qui sont impactées par mon manque de coordination (dû à mon TDAH). C’est surtout ma motricité fine mais voilà un résumé: les sports, le bricolage, le dessin, l’écriture, (j’ai appris à monter un vélo pour la première fous à 10 ans)..

Je ne parle jamais de mon TDAH comme un handicap mais cela en est un. J’aurai pu avoir des examens à part à la fac pour avoir plus de temps pendant mes examens (à cause du time-blindness), et puis j’ai des ÉNORMES soucis de coordination. Genre, vraiment.
Là elle s’est retournée et elle ne m’a plus adressé la parole, elle ne s’est même pas excusé.

Alors qu’elle n’arrêtait pas de m’insulter tout ce sue j’ai pu sortir à la dame c’était « il n’y a pas être méchante avec les gens comme ça... j’ai fait le plus vite possible mais si j’y vais plus lentement que vous c’est parce que j’ai un handicap... »

Dans mon Lidl dans le 94, personne ne m’aurait traité comme ça. Putain, il y avait une telle bonne solidarité entre les gens du quartier et ici je me suis fait insulté et en plus on a commencé à TOUCHER et ÉCARTER MES SACS avant même que je finisse de ranger mes affaires.

Depuis 6 ans, j’avais toujours vécu en banlieue. Moins d’une semaine que j’ai mon appart à Paris. Première fous que je fais les courses. Je me suis fait insulté.

Les Parisiens se plaignent car ils ont le « stéréotype » d’être froids, méchants et malpolis mais en même temps...
